BC0D859A7B064380A54C2E1719144325.description:
I can demonstrate understanding that the visual basis of ASL influences
meaning, with the implication that many words, phrases, idioms, and figurative expressions
do not translate directly from one language into another and vice versa. Examples:
Analyzing the concept of run (running water vs. running on foot vs. a runny nose);
researching iconic and arbitrary signs;

38BC0AE8BEF042478EA4542E9F72E329.description:
I can exchange views in ASL on topics from other content classes. Examples:
Comparing the pros and cons of recycling; describing the characters and plot of a novel;
explaining how different perspectives and angles in photography influence meaning.

C5ECDE299A2D48C488B90642F70A9F4D.description:
I can learn about and participate in activities enjoyed by young Deaf adults, such
as games, sports, ASL music, and entertainment. Examples: Playing the winking game;
viewing ASL films; attending local Deaf sport events.

2C29BC2283D84771A1D9F2B3F8B57755.description:
I can present results of a survey conducted on topics of personal interest or
pertaining to the Deaf community. Examples: Presenting on local Deaf demographics;
sharing unique life experiences; expressing opinions on a variety of topics.

12899CFCB2A54D7FBC45F92259B02549.description:
I can prepare research-based reports in ASL on current events and culture
relevant to the Deaf community. Examples: Researching events at Gallaudet University;
investigating ASL literature-related shows and exhibitions; describing controversial topics.
